(Ford GoBike System Data)¶

by (Youssef Hussein Ahmed)¶

Investigation Overview¶

  • In this investigation, I wanted to look at the features that could be used to predict the duration of variable trips.
  • The main focus was on the these 10 features:
    • start_time
    • end_time
    • start_station_latitude
    • start_station_longitude
    • end_station_latitude
    • end_station_longitude
    • user_type
    • member_birth_year
    • member_gender
    • bike_share_for_all_trip

Dataset Overview¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Distribution of Trips Durations¶

plt.title('Distribution Trips Durations')

plt.ylabel('Count')

# Log10 scale
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.hist(feat_df.duration_sec, bins= np.arange(61, 2e3+stp, stp))
plt.xscale('log')

x_ticks= [100, 200, 500, 1000]
plt.xticks(x_ticks, x_ticks)
plt.title('Distribution Trips Durations in Log10 Scale')
plt.xlabel('Duration (Sec)')
plt.ylabel('Count');
  • Duration is mostly centered on values that less than 2000 sec.
  • Trips number increases starting from around 1000 trip to 8500 trip in duration values up to 400 sec but then starts to decrease to less than 1000 trip in duration values that under 1300 sec.
  • Distribution in normal scale seemed to be a little right skewed but in log10 scale seemed to be normally distributed.

Distribution of Start Time and End Time¶

  • These variables has unfamiliar dtype (datetime64)..
  • I treated them as ordinal variables with intervals of hours or days.
  • By seprating each variable into 2 additional cols for ex: start_time can be seprated into:
    • start_time encoded into categorical variable with dayparts as categories.
    • day encoded into categorical variable with (Weekday, Weekend) as categories.

Relationship between Duration and User Type¶

In [21]:
plt.figure(figsize = [18, 6])

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
vp = sb.violinplot(data= feat_df, x= 'user_type', y= 'duration_sec', color= base_color, inner='quartile')
plt.ylim(0, 5e3)
plt.title("Duration Vs User Type (Violin Plot)")
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.ylabel('Duration (Sec)')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sb.boxplot(data= feat_df, x= 'user_type', y= 'duration_sec', color= base_color,)
plt.ylim(vp.get_ylim()); # set y-axis limits to be same as left plot
plt.title("Duration Vs User Type (Box Plot)")
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.ylabel('Duration (Sec)');
  • We know from univariate exploration that the largest percentage of riders are subscribers.
  • Here we notice, the median value of subscribers trips duration are about 500 sec while of customers are about 850.
  • There's a big number of outliers here but the most interesting is that customers trips are usually longer than subscribers.
  • Customer trips durations are usually about 500 to 1200 sec while the subscribers trips duration are usully about 300 to 750 sec

Relationship between Duration and Member Birth Year¶

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 5])
sb.regplot(data= feat_df, x= 'member_birth_year', y='duration_sec', scatter_kws={'alpha': 1/10}, fit_reg=False)
plt.ylim(0, 5e3)
plt.title("Member Birth Year vs Duration (Scatter Plot)")
plt.xlabel('Member Birth Year')
plt.ylabel('Duration (Sec)');
  • It seems there's a positive relationship between Member Birth Year and Duration
  • Starting from 40's borns to 2000's borns the durations increase from 500 sec up to more than 4k sec.

  • Obviously there's a strong correlations between sum features such as:

    • start_station_latitude vs start_station_longitude (-0.678105)
    • start_station_latitude vs end_station_latitude (0.990130)
    • start_station_longitude vs end_station_latitude (-0.682598)
    • start_station_longitude vs end_station_longitude (-0.685085)

  • These relationships worth to draw but unfortunately none of these features affect the duration

Encoding duration as third variable in strong correlations between features¶

Relationship between Member Birth Year & Duration encoding User Type (nominal) using color¶

g= sb.FacetGrid(data= feat_df, hue= 'user_type', height= 4, aspect= 3, palette= 'colorblind')
# Qualitative (all up to 6 colors): 'deep', 'pastel', 'dark', 'muted', 'bright', 'colorblind'
g.map(sb.regplot, 'member_birth_year', 'duration_sec', fit_reg= False, scatter_kws={'alpha': 0.5});

plt.xlim(1920)
plt.ylim(0, 4e4)
plt.title('Duration vs Member Birth Year encoding User Type')
plt.xlabel('Member Birth Year')
plt.ylabel('Duration (Sec)');
  • This is most intresting plot I could found.
  • It seems duration increases as member birth year grows.
  • There are 2 types of users: Customer or Subscribers.
  • Most of trips are made by subscribers while the longest trips are made by customers.
